00:34:03,028 --> 00:34:08,533
Whereas the city of Bedford has entered into a new ambulance service contract representing a significant change in public safety service delivery.

239
00:34:09,094 --> 00:34:15,179
And whereas questions have been raised regarding the negotiation process, financial management, in terms of service levels and cost implications of this transition.

240
00:34:15,899 --> 00:34:21,963
And whereas the City Council has a fiduciary responsibility to ensure taxpayer funds are used efficiently and public safety standards are maintained.

241
00:34:22,504 --> 00:34:29,929
Now, therefore, be it resolved that the Medford City Council hold a committee of the whole meeting to conduct a comprehensive review of the ambulance service contract negotiation process and transition.

242
00:34:29,989 --> 00:34:30,750
Councilor Scarpelli.

243
00:34:31,851 --> 00:34:34,552
Thank you, Mr. President.

244
00:34:36,534 --> 00:34:39,296
First, I'd like to thank everybody that's here tonight.

245
00:34:39,856 --> 00:34:40,897
This is something that

246
00:34:42,730 --> 00:34:58,454
When we received an email from the mayor back on December 10th to inform the council that we would be moving to negotiate our contract, the ambulance contract and open it up for negotiations, we applaud that.

247
00:34:58,514 --> 00:34:59,674
That's the mayor's prerogative.

248
00:35:00,214 --> 00:35:03,795
That's her role that the mayor oversees.

249
00:35:03,835 --> 00:35:08,757
The mayor oversees the contractual process in these types of positions.

250
00:35:11,372 --> 00:35:16,895
I will tell you on a personal level, as soon as I read that, I stopped, I froze.

251
00:35:17,175 --> 00:35:23,799
And there's a reason why I took such personal attention to this matter.

252
00:35:26,040 --> 00:35:36,205
My parents were both ambulatory and they were in a neighboring community that were at the time under another ambulance company.

253
00:35:38,626 --> 00:35:44,848
It's very difficult for a son to watch their mother and father pass and every little thing becomes magnified.

254
00:35:45,689 --> 00:35:56,173
And mom would, I would leave Medford to race over next door to wake her up at 4 o'clock in the morning.

255
00:35:56,513 --> 00:35:57,413
I'd help her get changed.

256
00:35:58,194 --> 00:36:04,576
I'd feed her her breakfast and we'd get ready to wait for our ambulance, our ride to Somerville for her dialysis treatment.

257
00:36:07,347 --> 00:36:23,815
And it was difficult because everything was serious, whether the ambulance was 10 minutes late, whether the straps were on too tight, whether they acknowledged her properly, whether she was warm, whether she felt comfortable with those people.

258
00:36:24,956 --> 00:36:29,038
And I can honestly say my mother didn't feel that way.

259
00:36:32,011 --> 00:36:43,099
I did everything I could to make sure that I did my due diligence as her son to make sure that I find a company that would service her so she felt comfortable.

260
00:36:45,861 --> 00:36:49,444
We switched for Armstrong, and Armstrong started picking her up.

261
00:36:50,865 --> 00:36:53,607
And instantly, they knew my mom's name.

262
00:36:54,508 --> 00:36:55,308
They were there early.

263
00:36:56,329 --> 00:36:57,290
My mom didn't have to wait.

264
00:36:58,532 --> 00:37:00,673
They gently would pick my mom off her seat.

265
00:37:01,014 --> 00:37:03,475
They would place her in the gurney.

266
00:37:03,715 --> 00:37:04,836
They would put her in the ambulance.

267
00:37:05,336 --> 00:37:06,177
And I would follow her.

268
00:37:07,037 --> 00:37:09,599
I would follow the ambulance to Somerville because that's what a good son does.

269
00:37:11,560 --> 00:37:18,544
And I would see my mom, go into dialysis, and I would watch the care that these professionals had for my mom.

270
00:37:21,626 --> 00:37:22,706
And then I would pick her up.

271
00:37:22,726 --> 00:37:23,427
I would leave work.

272
00:37:23,447 --> 00:37:24,608
I would take my lunch every day at 11.30.

273
00:37:26,080 --> 00:37:28,643
And I would wait for the ambulance, and they would pick mom up.

274
00:37:29,443 --> 00:37:37,130
And at the time, after a long, grueling dialysis session, they would take mom, who was just a puddle then, and take her home.

275
00:37:38,291 --> 00:37:39,212
They would carry her in.

276
00:37:39,452 --> 00:37:41,534
They would place her on her couch, on her seat.

277
00:37:42,095 --> 00:37:43,156
They'd make sure she was warm.

278
00:37:44,437 --> 00:37:46,539
And maybe once in a while, a little kiss on the forehead.

279
00:37:49,161 --> 00:37:52,364
So when I saw this, I said, what is going on here?

280
00:37:53,373 --> 00:38:01,577
what is happening to a service that this community has had for over 25 years, that we've had no issues, no concerns, no problems.

281
00:38:02,158 --> 00:38:04,419
They've always been there for us, no matter what.

282
00:38:05,139 --> 00:38:10,442
So I reached out to the mayor and I said, Madam Mayor, on a personal level, this is something very close to me.

283
00:38:11,082 --> 00:38:11,682
What are we doing?

284
00:38:11,702 --> 00:38:14,084
I think this is dangerous.

285
00:38:16,245 --> 00:38:20,227
Armstrong is the company that everyone should aspire to.

286
00:38:23,056 --> 00:38:26,918
The mayor said, I'll set up a meeting with the chiefs.

287
00:38:26,958 --> 00:38:27,638
They can explain.

288
00:38:28,758 --> 00:38:32,720
So I didn't know what was going on in the business side of the process.

289
00:38:33,300 --> 00:38:36,362
So I met with both Chief Evans and Chief Buckley via phone.

290
00:38:37,722 --> 00:38:41,124
And they shared a lot of information, a lot that shocked me.

291
00:38:42,644 --> 00:38:44,845
And I said, jeez, that's telling.

292
00:38:46,086 --> 00:38:50,808
And I understood that changing over an ambulance service, no matter what,

293
00:38:51,668 --> 00:38:54,809
is going to leave us in some jeopardy just because of that changeover.

294
00:38:56,190 --> 00:38:58,510
So public safety to me was paramount.

295
00:39:00,071 --> 00:39:03,112
Both Chief Buckley and Chief Evans explained the situations.

296
00:39:03,192 --> 00:39:05,093
I explained if they were part of the process.

297
00:39:05,613 --> 00:39:07,794
They both explained where they were on the process.

298
00:39:09,694 --> 00:39:12,355
I then reached out to Armstrong because I had that relationship.

299
00:39:13,235 --> 00:39:19,578
Because back when Mom was in Stoneham, I knew the process.

300
00:39:19,938 --> 00:39:20,738
I knew who to talk to.

301
00:39:21,649 --> 00:39:26,032
I'm an educated person who makes sure he does right by his parents.

302
00:39:27,914 --> 00:39:37,781
So I met with Armstrong, and I talked to Rich Raymond, I talked to Sean Mangan, and I asked them what's going on.

303
00:39:38,661 --> 00:39:39,822
And they explained the process.

304
00:39:40,482 --> 00:39:41,803
And I found something very alarming.

305
00:39:42,664 --> 00:39:47,988
I found that everything that my chiefs were saying, Armstrong was saying, yes, we'll do that.

306
00:39:49,329 --> 00:39:50,810
So I said, geez, there's a disconnect there.

307
00:39:52,645 --> 00:39:54,106
And then I started doing some homework.

308
00:39:54,146 --> 00:39:55,808
And I reached out to neighboring communities.

309
00:39:56,568 --> 00:39:59,170
I reached out to chiefs that had both services.

310
00:40:01,873 --> 00:40:02,793
And I found it alarming.

311
00:40:04,095 --> 00:40:05,095
And I talked to our chiefs.

312
00:40:05,155 --> 00:40:10,440
And I said, please reach out to these chiefs, police chiefs, fire chiefs, deputy chiefs.

313
00:40:10,620 --> 00:40:12,962
Ask them, get their input before we make this change.

314
00:40:14,163 --> 00:40:14,904
I talked to the mayor.

315
00:40:14,944 --> 00:40:16,104
I met with the mayor again.

316
00:40:16,205 --> 00:40:17,025
We had a conversation.

317
00:40:17,045 --> 00:40:20,068
I said, Madam Mayor, thank you for setting up the meeting.

318
00:40:20,802 --> 00:40:22,643
I appreciate that, but there's definitely a disconnect.

319
00:40:23,604 --> 00:40:25,064
I've talked to neighboring communities.

320
00:40:25,205 --> 00:40:26,285
Have you spoken with them?

321
00:40:26,745 --> 00:40:31,328
And quote, unquote, the mayor said, geez, George, you're giving me more work, but I'll definitely look into it.

322
00:40:32,349 --> 00:40:40,213
And I know that our chiefs did their due diligence because I talked to the chiefs from neighboring communities, reached back out and said, yeah, they talked to our chiefs.

323
00:40:40,893 --> 00:40:43,155
And I said, great, so let's move this forward.

324
00:40:44,232 --> 00:41:03,322
And as the process went on, I then reached back out to the mayor in a text, and I said, I think the chiefs were on that, and I said, as we sat through the process, and I'm not part of the process, but I think there's a huge problem here that at the 13th hour, it seems to be that I'm the only one talking to all the parties.

325
00:41:04,563 --> 00:41:06,824
I'm the only one that's listening to everybody.

326
00:41:06,864 --> 00:41:13,508
So I said, please, can you sit one more time with everybody so we don't make any mistakes?

327
00:41:14,462 --> 00:41:18,123
Now, the other company, come in and be great.

328
00:41:18,543 --> 00:41:20,043
It's not about the other company.

329
00:41:20,863 --> 00:41:24,464
This is about the company we have today, the company we've had for over 25 years.

330
00:41:27,265 --> 00:41:36,527
And I was told that the five members on the committee all feel strong enough that they all supported this change.

331
00:41:36,567 --> 00:41:37,067
We needed it.

332
00:41:39,058 --> 00:41:42,960
And there's a lot of things that that have to come out.

333
00:41:43,220 --> 00:41:53,043
And that's why I've asked to send this to a committee of the whole next week and possibly ask the chair to possibly look at executive session so we can talk about more in depth information.

334
00:41:54,024 --> 00:42:01,927
I know people in this room are very angry with me because this is happening because the fear of or the understanding of that calling

335
00:42:03,473 --> 00:42:09,019
Armstrong out and putting them on the spot tonight is something that's going to be detrimental to our community.

336
00:42:10,680 --> 00:42:20,210
To the contrary, because what Rich Raymond did, Rich Raymond stood up and said, George, listen, I'm willing to come and do anything that needs to be done so everybody understands the process.

337
00:42:21,731 --> 00:42:23,393
That's how important Method is to them.

338
00:42:25,718 --> 00:42:33,301
To the point where even Rich said, if anything happens, no matter if it's with the other company here or with the other company, if something goes bad, we're going to be here anyway from Medford.

339
00:42:33,321 --> 00:42:35,101
Because that's the type of people they are.

340
00:42:36,722 --> 00:42:48,786
So I felt strong enough, no matter how people that I respect immensely felt by me bringing this forward was a mistake, I needed to make sure that I brought this forward because it is important.

341
00:42:50,486 --> 00:42:52,467
I gave you my perspective as a son.

342
00:42:55,112 --> 00:42:59,996
But now I'm talking to you as a city councilor that's looking at our community's public safety.

343
00:43:01,877 --> 00:43:03,678
So there are a lot of things that we'll move forward.

344
00:43:04,279 --> 00:43:12,524
The social media's gone out, and they've chimed in, and they've gotten word something about contracts and money and this and that.

345
00:43:14,126 --> 00:43:21,611
If that's the case, that's why we want to go to executive session and committee the whole meeting relatively quick.

346
00:43:23,219 --> 00:43:26,821
But tonight, I wanted to bring this forward to understand that this is important.

347
00:43:28,101 --> 00:43:45,169
And if you talk to neighboring communities, and you talk to them, and they share just the fear of turning over ambulance companies, the fear of something bad possibly happening, percentage has increased dramatically.

348
00:43:47,390 --> 00:43:50,091
I don't want anybody in our community to be that percentage.

349
00:43:51,512 --> 00:43:52,152
It's not worth it.

350
00:43:54,680 --> 00:44:10,868
And like I said, if when I talked to our administration, our team, and they said A, B, and C, and then I spoke with the leadership from Armstrong, and they said exactly what was being said, I would say, well, you made your bed.

351
00:44:10,948 --> 00:44:11,648
We need to move on.

352
00:44:12,609 --> 00:44:13,469
But it was the opposite.

353
00:44:15,070 --> 00:44:15,850
It was the opposite.

354
00:44:17,211 --> 00:44:18,792
When they talked about the behavior bus,

355
00:44:20,361 --> 00:44:21,442
We'll use that for an example.

356
00:44:21,522 --> 00:44:35,829
That being one of the key points why Medford went with this new company, that we can work with mental health and drug abuse in a more swifter, more controlled fashion to get people help faster.

357
00:44:38,451 --> 00:44:46,055
I had a great conversation with Rich in understanding that this process was started three years ago first to do this here in Medford.

358
00:44:47,576 --> 00:44:49,957
And then it was brought up in negotiations

359
00:44:52,528 --> 00:44:53,328
And then it stopped.

360
00:44:54,909 --> 00:45:02,870
So there are things that were presented to the public that I think for city council, for the people I represent, we need to clear the air so we can move on.

361
00:45:03,271 --> 00:45:07,011
Whether there's a way we could stop this and stay with Armstrong or whether you move on.

362
00:45:11,192 --> 00:45:19,114
So I'm not here to entertain any of the other options of why we did this, why we did that.

363
00:45:20,295 --> 00:45:21,675
My perspective is very simple.

364
00:45:22,960 --> 00:45:24,001
I spoke to all the parties.

365
00:45:28,865 --> 00:45:32,208
I went through what Armstrong did for my loved ones.

366
00:45:35,391 --> 00:45:41,837
I see a deep issue here with the lack of communication with people that are sitting down at the table.

367
00:45:43,639 --> 00:45:45,921
So that being said, Council President,

368
00:45:49,289 --> 00:45:52,371
There's a reason why that we need a more robust conversation.

369
00:45:52,932 --> 00:46:06,662
I think sending this to Committee of the Whole so we could talk about, more importantly, what a response time looks like so residents can understand how amazing Armstrong is.

370
00:46:07,822 --> 00:46:16,649
We can talk about the different pieces that were important in that contract that Armstrong has already given us and continue to give to us.

371
00:46:19,130 --> 00:46:23,412
Having that meeting in an open forum where we can talk openly, I think it's important.

372
00:46:24,632 --> 00:46:34,256
So I would ask that we motion to take this to Committee of the Whole with possibilities, if using private information, that we go to executive session.

373
00:46:34,896 --> 00:46:44,700
And again, I apologize for my emotion, but it means something to me.

374
00:46:46,901 --> 00:46:48,162
But the way I looked at it is this.

375
00:46:49,134 --> 00:46:52,876
there's another Lily Scarpelli that's going through dialysis today.

376
00:46:54,416 --> 00:47:00,999
And I don't know if she has a son or a daughter that can do what my sister and myself did.

377
00:47:02,600 --> 00:47:04,221
So that's why I'm going to fight for this.

378
00:47:04,561 --> 00:47:06,982
So, Mr. President, I make that motion.

379
00:47:07,102 --> 00:47:07,382
Thank you.

380
00:47:09,030 --> 00:47:10,250
Thank you, Councilor Scarpelli.

381
00:47:11,550 --> 00:47:17,812
On the motion, and we'll get to discussion in a second, but on the motion of Councilor Scarpelli to refer to Committee of the Whole, seconded by Councilor Sang.

382
00:47:18,632 --> 00:47:22,592
We will first hear from the rest of members of the council if they'd like to speak on this.

383
00:47:23,873 --> 00:47:27,593
I'll say something quickly, and then we will hear from members of the public.

384
00:47:27,993 --> 00:47:34,235
And just a reminder to members of the public, you can speak either here in person or on Zoom, and you'll have three minutes.

385
00:47:34,315 --> 00:47:36,055
But first, we're gonna go to members of the council.

386
00:47:36,155 --> 00:47:36,755
Councilor Sang.

387
00:47:38,991 --> 00:47:43,013
I want to thank you and applaud you for your leadership on this issue, Councilor Scarpelli.

388
00:47:45,434 --> 00:47:47,015
Don't apologize for your emotion, I think.

389
00:47:48,156 --> 00:48:01,023
It really brings to light the significance of why this is important for our city and important for the council to get involved and be talking about making sure that we are all communicating with each other on such a profound change like this.

390
00:48:02,124 --> 00:48:03,725
And I think your story is

391
00:48:04,707 --> 00:48:06,068
was profoundly touching.

392
00:48:06,508 --> 00:48:25,177
I think it's a story that a lot of our residents know, see every single day, have lived, and, you know, through the last few decades as well, through the, I think, really top-notch and faithful service that Armstrong has given to this city.

393
00:48:27,658 --> 00:48:47,289
I think moving to executive, to committee of the whole and then possibly to executive session if that's allowed will be really important for us to speak in more depth and in more, more freely about this, about the issue.

394
00:48:48,450 --> 00:48:53,473
I've certainly in talking to you, in talking to residents,

395
00:48:54,673 --> 00:48:57,356
have questions about the change.

396
00:48:58,016 --> 00:49:02,301
I mean, the first one you brought up, what does this transition look like?

397
00:49:02,341 --> 00:49:03,182
Are we ready for it?

398
00:49:03,482 --> 00:49:07,526
Are our first responders ready for this change?

399
00:49:08,928 --> 00:49:11,190
What does that look like and what should residents expect?

400
00:49:11,230 --> 00:49:16,696
I think that's a baseline question we need to answer with any large shift like this.

401
00:49:18,797 --> 00:49:25,960
I think in addition to that, I mean, I would ask why we made the change and what the process was behind it.

402
00:49:27,361 --> 00:49:35,385
I think there are a lot of residents, as you kind of alluded to, that have brought up important critiques, concerns, questions.

403
00:49:36,025 --> 00:49:42,328
And at the very least, the role of city government, if we've taken any lesson from the last few months, is to explain

404
00:49:43,168 --> 00:49:52,115
large changes like this better to a resident so that everyone has as full of a picture as, you know, as we all deserve.

405
00:49:53,656 --> 00:49:59,421
You know, I think residents have brought up things like, you know, have we compared response times?

406
00:50:01,102 --> 00:50:06,426
If there was a problem with the service before, what did we do wrong?

407
00:50:06,726 --> 00:50:08,308
What did, was it fixed?

408
00:50:09,359 --> 00:50:11,420
where there are offers for those problems to be fixed.

409
00:50:12,901 --> 00:50:23,565
Residents have brought up union issues as well, and I think it's important for this council to stand by working folks and union leadership.

410
00:50:25,667 --> 00:50:43,333
We've talked about, I think, the rates of mutual aid between companies, what the behavior bus actually looks like, whether that benefit is something that can be done with Armstrong, as you talked to.

411
00:50:46,014 --> 00:50:53,437
And I think there are larger structural questions, too, outside of just the ambulance issue that we've seen over the last few months.

412
00:50:54,072 --> 00:51:06,955
where I think the state law and the charter are really clear about who is the person, who is the individual in the city, who is responsible for entering and negotiating contracts.

413
00:51:07,495 --> 00:51:18,237
But I think there are structural questions that perhaps have to come in a few years when we review the charter, when we look at the council's ability, the balance of power between different offices in the city about

414
00:51:19,849 --> 00:51:24,033
that ability to enter and negotiate contracts and exit contracts as well.

415
00:51:24,533 --> 00:51:34,042
But I think we'll have time in the committee as a whole to talk more about these issues, to talk more deeply about these issues as well.

416
00:51:35,082 --> 00:51:38,505
But just for today, I'm very happy to support this motion.

417
00:51:41,648 --> 00:51:42,049
Thank you.

418
00:51:42,349 --> 00:51:45,091
Any other members of the council want to speak to this paper at this time?

419
00:51:45,171 --> 00:51:45,792
Councilor Lemming.

420
00:51:47,923 --> 00:52:00,827
I would just like to thank my colleague for thoroughly doing his research on this and sharing his own story of why this matters so much.

421
00:52:02,307 --> 00:52:06,628
Just to voice my own opinions on this, this is a resolution that I support.

422
00:52:06,668 --> 00:52:17,071
I think at the very least, residents would like clarity on the back and forth, what exactly happened and what the real world impacts of this will be.

423
00:52:18,085 --> 00:52:24,947
I think Committee of the Whole with a possible executive session is the perfect forum to do that.

424
00:52:24,967 --> 00:52:40,873
I look forward to hearing folks speak about this issue, to hear from the many folks who, from the many EMS workers that we have in the room tonight who would be interested, who would offer their perspectives on this.

425
00:52:45,310 --> 00:52:58,513
I hope that this body can be useful in at least clarifying the reasons behind this change, because a lot of residents have been reaching out to us and are clearly very dissatisfied with it.

426
00:52:58,573 --> 00:53:01,734
So thank you once again for bringing this forward.

427
00:53:07,205 --> 00:53:15,267
Seeing no further councilors want to speak to this at this time, I'll just be brief about my viewpoint on this.

428
00:53:16,147 --> 00:53:28,090
I think when we talk about our ambulance contract, we're talking about residents wanting to trust that if they get sick or if they get hurt,

429
00:53:29,122 --> 00:53:42,433
there will be an EMT and an ambulance at their door or at the scene of a collision or at the scene of an incident quickly so that they can get the help that they need.

430
00:53:43,614 --> 00:53:49,618
It's one of the things that is one of the most essential functions of government, right?

431
00:53:50,339 --> 00:53:54,843
Making sure that if something goes wrong, there's someone there to keep folks safe.

432
00:53:55,843 --> 00:53:57,685
And I think when it comes to this contract,

433
00:53:59,241 --> 00:54:23,533
When you've been working with a group, a company for over 20 years, when there's been relationships built between those EMS folks and your police and your fire department, I would ask, and I would wanna know, and those are the questions that I'm asking, why change and why and how will residents be safer if we change?

434
00:54:24,600 --> 00:54:26,421
And that isn't clear to me.

435
00:54:26,601 --> 00:54:38,444
You know, I also have had a chance to speak with the mayor and our fire chief and our police chief, with Councilor Scarpelli, with some folks from Armstrong.

436
00:54:39,204 --> 00:54:41,065
And, you know, it's not clear to me.

437
00:54:41,105 --> 00:54:44,186
I've heard a couple of stories of things that happened that I don't like.

438
00:54:44,886 --> 00:54:45,806
I raised those with Armstrong.

439
00:54:45,826 --> 00:54:46,967
They said we didn't like that either.

440
00:54:48,347 --> 00:54:49,147
